<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,1569,1875]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,464,1649,1675]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Description.</emphasis>
Colour: Brown when dried or preserved in alcohol, presumably green in life (not recorded). Shape: Lobate, size 
<quantity box="[744,819,1689,1715]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="cm" value="25.0">25 cm</quantity>
<date box="[829,883,1689,1715]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1910-10">
x 
<quantity box="[854,883,1689,1715]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="cm" value="10.0">10</quantity>
</date>
cm, attached to hard substrata, with hollow upright, finger­like projections up to 
<quantity box="[789,847,1729,1755]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="cm" value="7.0">7 cm</quantity>
high. Oscula are distinct, 
<quantity box="[1155,1253,1729,1755]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 mm</quantity>
wide, and scattered over the surface (
<figureCitation box="[626,751,1769,1795]" captionStart="FIGURE 2. A" captionStartId="4.[264,367,1740,1764]" captionTargetBox="[314,1272,313,1713]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[314,1273,304,1713]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A. Amphimedon chloros Ilan et al., 2004, habit (scale bar = 1 cm); B. Amphimedon chloros Ilan et al., 2004, structure of the ectosomal skeleton showing the three­dimensional network of spicule tracts (scale bar = 0.5 mm); C – F. SEM­images of oxeas of Amphimedon chloros (C), A. dinae sp. nov. (D), A. jalae sp. nov. (E) and A. hamadai sp. nov. (F) (scale bars = 10 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170842/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figure 
<number box="[712,728,1769,1795]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). Surface: Optically smooth, slightly bumpy surface. Punctate due to regularly distributed subdermal spaces. Texture: Compressible, soft, easy to tear.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170842/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" targetBox="[314,1272,313,1713]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1323,1740,1877]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
